The AI capability needed here is using analogies you haven't though of or personally experience. 
AI has a lot of data from many perspectives that can make connections you wouldn't reach on your own. 
In landscaping, for example, I've never run over a rabbits nest but someone else has that is an experience 
that can be connected to a technology concept. It uses someone experience to create another experience. 

Human's strength lies within their unique reactions to the same experiences.  
For example, running over a rabbit's nest will make someone feel guilty, some numb, sad, or even a sense of power. 
That different range of personal emotion AI can reference for you to connect to a concept and really understand due to your emotional detachment to that experience. 
AI is strong at pattern-matching across thousands of "someone had this exact physical experience" moments and offering you two or three candidate analogies to choose from — casting a wide net you couldn't cast alone, since you can only draw from your own actual memories.

 AI proposes an analogy from its broader pool, and you're the one who tests it against your real memory — does this actually match what running the mower over something felt like, or does it fall flat? If it falls flat, you push back and AI tries again. 





